{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631449"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17373"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70360"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10063"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55824"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5432"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23624"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70360"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to your general practice with fever, severe headache, and neck stiffness. You suspect bacterial meningitis based on her clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the legal requirement for disease notification in Australia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Only fatal cases require notification","Both confirmed and suspected cases must be notified","Notification is voluntary for medical practitioners","Only laboratory-confirmed cases require notification","Only cases resulting in hospitalisation require notification"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia, \u003Cstrong\u003Eboth confirmed and suspected cases must be notified\u003C/strong\u003E to relevant public health authorities. This requirement is mandated by legislation and applies to specified infectious diseases, with different timeframes for notification depending on the disease\u0027s public health significance. For example, suspected meningococcal disease requires immediate notification to enable urgent public health action including contact tracing and prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly laboratory-confirmed cases require notification\u003C/strong\u003E - Waiting for laboratory confirmation could delay important public health responses, potentially putting contacts at risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly cases resulting in hospitalisation require notification\u003C/strong\u003E - Many notifiable diseases may not require hospitalisation but still need public health action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENotification is voluntary for medical practitioners\u003C/strong\u003E - Disease notification is a legal requirement under public health legislation, not voluntary\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly fatal cases require notification\u003C/strong\u003E - Waiting for fatal outcomes would severely compromise public health responses and prevention efforts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrompt notification allows public health authorities to implement control measures, conduct contact tracing, and monitor disease trends effectively. For diseases like meningococcal infection, immediate notification can be life-saving by enabling rapid prophylaxis of close contacts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Notifiable diseases must be reported to public health authorities by law to enable monitoring and control of infectious diseases.","Healthcare providers are legally required to report both confirmed and suspected cases of notifiable diseases.","The time frame for notification varies by disease, with some requiring immediate notification and others allowing up to 5 days."],"references":["Notifiable infectious diseases, conditions and micro-organisms. Department of Health; Victoria. Updated October 14, 2024. Available from: https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/notifiable-infectious-diseases-conditions-and-micro-organisms"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55824"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55824"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T19:48:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T19:49:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10063"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70360"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"